properties.description: Relatively level tee shot with a ridge line running down the right side of the hole. Bunker short right off the tee and long left. Tee shot should be placed down the left side of the fairway because the approach.
Tee shot plays downhill 9 meters with back left and back of the green sitting on the lake. Right side of green is protected by two bunkers. This will be a very visually dramatic golf hole.

Short Par 4 with a level tee shot and a fairway bunker short left and long right. Tee shot should be placed down the right side close to the fairway bunker because approach shot opens up from there. If tee shot is down left side a green side bunker comes into play.

Long Par 5 with a slight downhill tee shot. A  big ridge runs down the right side of the hole that helps frame the tee shot as well. Second shot plays almost level and should be played close to fairway bunkers right of the 2nd landing area so you have an open approach shot into the green.

Dramatic downhill tee shot that drops approx. 8 meters and will offer very dramatic view. Also a big ridge runs down the left side of the hole and a big ridge frames the right side of the hole to the right of the 2nd landing area. Tee shot should be placed down the right side of the fairway as close as possible to the fairway bunker because the approach to the green opens up from here. The second shot plays downhill approx. 2 meters .

Long Par 4 with a tee shot playing uphill over 5 meters. Very dramatic bunkers cut into left and right side of the fairway as it starts its climb uphill. Approach shot plays downhill to a very large  green. This green is protected by bunkers short right of the green and to the left.

Tee shot on this medium length Par 3 plays downhill approx. 2 meters and is framed down the right side of the hole by a big ridge line. The back of the green sits right on the lake. A bunker guards the right side of the green.

A short Par 4 that plays relatively level from tee thru the green and is framed by the canal down the left side and a big ridge right of the landing area with a fairway bunker cut into it. The tee shot should be placed close to this fairway bunker so you have an open approach into the green.

This medium length Par 5 is framed by the canal down the left side of the hole and a ridge to the right and plays relatively level the length of the hole. 3 bunkers are located left of the 1st landing area and a bunker to the right. The second shot should be placed as close to the fairway bunker located to the right of the 2nd landing area as possible to leave an open approach to the green. The entire front left half of the green is blocked by two green side bunkers.

This medium length Par 4 has a lake running down the entire left side of the hole framing it as well as a ridge to the right of the fairway and behind the green. The tee shot plays downhill approx. 3 meters and should be placed as close to the right side of the fairway bunker as possible so you have an open approach. The second shot plays uphill over 3 meters and is set in an amphitheater setting which will be very visually dramatic.
A short Par 3 which drops over 6 meters from the tee to green. The green is surrounded by bunkers on all sides and because of the elevation on this hole it will be very dramatic.

This Par 4 has a lake running down the entire left side of the hole and a ridge running down the right side and behind the green. The tee shot drops approx. 3 meters and the approach shot plays relatively level. The closer the tee shot plays to the lake the more open your approach shot into the green will be.

This reachable Par 5 plays slightly downhill from the tee and is framed down the right side of the hole by a small ridge line and by bunkers both right and left of the first landing area. Between the 1st landing area and the green is a series of â€œcross bunkersâ€ used often by Alister Mackenzie the designer of Augusta National who was famous for using cross bunkers and camouflage bunkers. The green will have a small bunker blocking the center of the green and one to the right as well. This hole will be memorable because of its bunkers.

This short Par 4 plays relatively level from tee to green and is framed by a big ridge to the right of the landing area. A small bunker located directly in front of the green will dictate if you should play your tee shot down the  right side of the fairway.

A long Par 4 that plays slightly downhill off the tee and uphill into the green. The tee shot should be placed down the right side of the fairway to leave an open approach into the green which is guarded to the left by two bunkers.

This long Par 3 is framed by the canal which runs down the left side of the hole and also cuts in front of the tee shot. From the tee you must carry the water to reach the approach area before the green. A small bunker guards the front of the green.

This medium length Par 5 plays downhill over 6 meters from the tee and then plays slightly uphill towards the green. A ridge line frames the right side of the 1st landing area. The second shot is a risk/reward shot. If you play safe to the right fairway on your second shot your approach will be partially blocked by bunkers. If you play your  shot to the left fairway you can possibly reach the green in two shots and if not you will have an open approach. The two fairways are separated by a series of three bunkers. The green is set in a very dramatic amphitheater setting. I believe this will become one of Qizhiong GC most memorable holes.

A medium length Par 4 that plays slightly downhill from tee to green and is framed by a ridge down the right side of the hole and a lake down the left side of the hole. The green sits approx. 6 meters below the clubhouse which is a dramatic backdrop for this hole. The approach shot into the green will be memorable because of the clubhouse sitting on the hillside directly behind the green. Combine all these elements and this is a dramatic finishing hole.
